WEBVTT

00:00:02.470 --> 00:00:04.000
Can people hear me?

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Is the mic turned on?

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
It's on?

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Let me...

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Can I clip it down the shirt?

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Thank you for your patience.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:24.990
Cool.

00:00:24.990 --> 00:00:28.000
Can people hear me now?

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Yes.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:28.600
I did.

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:30.000
Okay, awesome.

00:00:30.470 --> 00:00:32.000
Please bear with me.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:33.020
I'm kind of breaking a little bit.

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:36.000
I'm following two of my heroes from the industry, and

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.570
also I've basically had to completely revise my entire talk on

00:00:38.570 --> 00:00:42.000
the fly as a result of the earlier keynote.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:44.000
So let's do this.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.430
This is about the third-ish time I've given this

00:00:48.430 --> 00:00:50.590
talk, but I've done it for completely different audiences the

00:00:50.590 --> 00:00:51.380
other two times.

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:53.840
The first time was for a group mostly of publishers in London

00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:54.800
at Protocols for Publishers.

00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:59.560
The second time was for more of a journalism tech audience,

00:00:59.630 --> 00:01:02.550
mostly like journalism consumers, and this one's more for builders

00:01:02.550 --> 00:01:04.000
and people who are in this space.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
And kind of the idea I'm going to be talking about

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
is how can journalism start using the tools available in the atmosphere

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.610
to start creating its own algorithms, and I'll talk about

00:01:15.610 --> 00:01:16.000
why it's important.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.000
First off, a little bit about myself.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.720
I work and have worked in news media since 2013 or so

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:25.800
, but my background has always been kind of journalism and/

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:28.000
or tech kind of on some level.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.000
I moved from Canada to London in 2011.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.000
I also went to the UBC at one point.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.000
It's really cool to be on this campus again.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:39.260
But I ended up in London.

00:01:39.260 --> 00:01:44.000
I currently work at a financial newspaper doing fancy charts mainly.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.700
But I've had bylines in various papers, including Financial

00:01:48.700 --> 00:01:51.000
Times, Times and Sunday Times, Economist, Guardian,

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:52.000
etc.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
And yeah, so I arrived in kind of like the decentralized

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:00.000
social media space because I find it really interesting in terms of

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
how do we how can the space be used to present a

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:10.660
idea of journalism that can be seen in ways that are censorship

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:14.190
resistant, that gives publishers more control over how their content is

00:02:14.190 --> 00:02:16.000
distributed, etc.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And so I started initially on Mastodon.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
I was I created an instance on Mastodon called

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:22.000
foreststate.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
media way back in 2018.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
I think it was the very first journalism related instance on the

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Fediverse.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:28.000
I might be wrong about that.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Please correct me if I am.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
It didn't really go anywhere.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
I got maybe like five users and I shut it down literally

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.000
the week that Musk took over Twitter.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Which was probably a good move in hindsight.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
I kind of, you know, fell out of love with

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:50.200
ActivityPub as a way of distributing journalism because there

00:02:50.200 --> 00:02:52.900
's some topographical kind of issues of the network that I

00:02:52.900 --> 00:02:56.000
kind of found frustrating and then I, you know, I

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:02.000
got a blue sky invite in 2023 and I really enjoyed being

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:02.920
on the atmosphere.

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:08.000
I built a few different things probably most notably the verified news

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.540
feed and also the trending news feed which I'll be talking

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:12.000
about a little bit in a second.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
So yeah.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Approaching this from two ways.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
AT Pro needs journalists.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.900
I think that journalism is a very core function of any social

00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:28.000
media platform.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
My theory of change.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.470
You need to have all the following for a effective social media

00:03:33.470 --> 00:03:36.000
network that kind of is a center of conversation.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.150
You start with the creatives, the shit posters, the

00:03:40.150 --> 00:03:43.000
people who are doing artsy fun things on this brave new

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.000
platform that no one's really ever heard of yet.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And, you know, those are kind of like the people

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
who start the platform, who build interest for it, who

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.000
pull interest from other people who will eventually join.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Academics are another big part of a healthy social network.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Seeing all this stuff at AT Science yesterday was just like super

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:08.000
, super cool.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.470
And it's really exciting to see so much work happening kind

00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:12.000
of in that space.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Any journalists.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Because journalists talk about what's happening on these platforms, they

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.290
are a big part of why they're seen as being socially

00:04:21.290 --> 00:04:22.000
relevant.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:27.000
And journalists kind of follow the creative types eventually.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
And following the journalists you also get politicians.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.370
And I see politicians as a big driver of people joining the

00:04:34.370 --> 00:04:40.000
social network because people want to talk to their elected representatives.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
The elected representatives want to talk to the constituents.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
It's important for the health of an ongoing social network.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.750
And then following all those groups, you get celebrities which are

00:04:50.750 --> 00:04:54.000
really the kind of draw of like the other 90% of

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:54.000
the social platform.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
People like to follow celebrities because they're curious what the people

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:58.000
who they're excited about are.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
And like lastly, pornography is also like a really big part

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
of what makes a healthy social network in my mind.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.430
And I think that, I have an idea for a talking

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:08.710
I've been going to do next year about why I think

00:05:08.710 --> 00:05:10.000
that's the case.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.000
But anyways, I'm going to talk specifically about journalism.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.620
And I think that the atmosphere is really important for journalism right

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:22.000
now because right now we have so much of our media ecosystem

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:30.000
influenced by for-profit social networks like Twitter, Facebook,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:30.000
etc.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:37.440
and this chart is from Magnitude Media using a data source

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:40.000
called Junkipedia which looks at social media traffic.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.680
And it breaks down the most partisan-leaning political accounts

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:47.000
on X in February.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.280
And, suffice to say, one of those circles is

00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:55.000
able to kind of impact the discourse a little bit.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.550
If only, it's a bit bigger is all I'm

00:05:58.630 --> 00:05:59.000
saying.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:05.720
And I guess, you know, kind of why I like

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:10.080
all this stuff interests me is because when I was going to

00:06:10.090 --> 00:06:12.180
journalism school back in like 2011 like a huge part of what

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:15.000
you're taught is how do you maintain a Twitter following?

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:17.000
How do you engage with your audience?

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:21.000
How do you use social media for sourcing news coverage?

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:22.760
And that's a big part of the day-to-

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:24.000
day life of journalists.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:27.410
And my personal belief, and I should mention that, pretty

00:06:27.410 --> 00:06:30.000
much everything I'm saying is just completely all just my opinions

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:30.000
.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
I'm not reflective of any employer I've ever had.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.150
But my feeling is maybe the reason why the discourse is a

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:39.530
little bit cooked is because the majority of journalists are spending a

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:45.210
huge amount of their time on social networks that both elevate and

00:06:45.210 --> 00:06:48.990
incentivize far-right content.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:55.000
So, AT Pro needs journalists.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
But also, I think journalism needs AT Pro.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.360
I think AT Pro solves a lot of the fundamental needs that

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:06.000
you have for social network as a media organization.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.590
And I'll get into a few of those in a second

00:07:09.630 --> 00:07:10.000
.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
Why I think this is the case.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.270
A lot of these charts are from the Reuters Digital News

00:07:15.270 --> 00:07:16.000
Report.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
They track something called news avoidance.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.090
And I'm going to show us in three different charts or

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:23.000
different metrics.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.640
This is from the 2024 edition because I couldn't find this

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:27.990
longitudinal kind of data for 2025 yet.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:34.310
So, this shows the proportion of people who reported using no

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:36.980
sources of news in the last week.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
They just completely managed to avoid all the news headlines.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.400
And in the last like 10 years, it's grown by

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:45.990
about like roughly 10%, especially amongst younger age cohorts.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.230
Further, you have the amount of people who are extremely or

00:07:50.230 --> 00:07:56.000
very interested in news has declined substantially since 2015.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.580
To a point where the 18 to 24 demographic, only 33

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:03.990
% are extremely or very interested in news.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.710
This is from the 2025 data showing just the breakdown globally of

00:08:08.710 --> 00:08:10.000
news avoidance.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:14.990
40% of all people surveyed are avoiding the news.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
It's even bigger in like the younger cohorts.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.150
In the 25 to 34 cohort, a whole 43% of

00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:24.000
readers are actively avoiding the news.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.990
So, like, what's driving this?

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.120
I kind of feel in some ways that a big part of

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:37.000
it is the way in which algorithms deliver news to readers.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:41.990
And it's very overwhelming and it prioritizes engagement over news

00:08:42.010 --> 00:08:45.000
worthiness or public understanding.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:49.170
And as a result of that burnout, you have people who

00:08:49.170 --> 00:08:51.990
are moving to AI as a primary source of news.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.010
This is the proportion that used AI chat box for news in

00:08:55.010 --> 00:08:56.000
the last week.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
This is also from the Reuters digital news report.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:05.470
And it kind of is towards about 10% kind of globally

00:09:05.510 --> 00:09:05.990
.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:12.000
And further, news leaders understand this challenge.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.920
50% think it's going to be like a slow burn

00:09:14.920 --> 00:09:17.000
kind of impact on the industry.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:18.600
And 20% thinks it's going to be the next big

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:19.000
thing.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.200
So, regardless, about 70% of news leaders think it

00:09:21.290 --> 00:09:23.000
's going to have an impact on the industry.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:28.510
And yet, despite all this, social media continues to be

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:30.990
a major source of news.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And in fact, it's growing.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.660
If you look at that orange line, that's the US

00:09:36.670 --> 00:09:37.000
.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.590
In 2025, the US joined what Reuters refers to as

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:45.210
the Social First Club, which is countries that where a majority

00:09:45.210 --> 00:09:48.990
of people get their news primarily initially from social media.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.650
So, we need to make social work as a place that

00:09:52.670 --> 00:09:54.000
people get news.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.410
Because if we don't, then the incumbents will continue

00:09:57.410 --> 00:09:58.000
doing so.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.770
And the quality of our discourse will just deteriorate over time

00:10:01.780 --> 00:10:02.000
.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:07.000
This is alluded to in the last talk.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:08.820
And I'm going to go through it very, very briefly

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:09.000
.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.330
But this is my brief and incomplete recent history of algorithmic

00:10:12.330 --> 00:10:13.000
fuckery.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.000
So, this only goes back to 2015.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
I'm sure there are more examples that you can use.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.720
And these are just a half dozen I just picked out of

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:23.000
a hat, basically.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
But these are the ones that kind of impact me.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.340
Google Accelerated Mobile Pages, AMP is one of

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:29.000
them.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:32.290
Google said, hey, if you use this new technology that

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:35.780
makes news faster to download and read, we'll boost you

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:37.000
in terms of page rank.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.650
And I think that had a pretty negative effect on the quality

00:10:39.650 --> 00:10:41.990
of news that was being served by Google.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:46.000
As mentioned in the last talk, there was pivot to video

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:46.000
.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.650
And I have another personal kind of connection to this in that

00:10:49.660 --> 00:10:53.450
I'm from the generation of journalists who sort of graduated journalism

00:10:53.490 --> 00:10:55.000
school while pivot to video was happening.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:00.000
And it was devastating for an entire generation of journalists.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.470
And I'm not sure it's kind of like the young

00:11:03.470 --> 00:11:06.650
core journalists that I've really even fully recovered from at this

00:11:06.650 --> 00:11:06.990
point.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.740
In 2022, you have Musk taking over Twitter and depriorit

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:14.980
izing outgoing links, which has had a major impact on news

00:11:14.980 --> 00:11:15.980
traffic.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.670
In 2023, you had Facebook blocking Canadian titles because of the

00:11:20.670 --> 00:11:22.000
Online Media Act.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.000
Can't get Canadian news on Facebook no more.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.380
And in 2024, you started to see AI overviews start

00:11:28.380 --> 00:11:31.990
to become a thing on Google, which has had a really

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.800
massive impact on the traffic that news orgs receive from organic

00:11:36.810 --> 00:11:38.000
search.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.380
Before this one, I've also added like a 2026

00:11:40.480 --> 00:11:41.000
edition.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:42.000
There's a few more things.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:43.000
These are kind of like just loosely related.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.520
I know they're not quite on topic with it, but

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:47.990
you had like TikTok being sold to Oracle.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.870
So you have a major upcoming channel for news be sold to

00:11:52.870 --> 00:12:00.010
a company for ultimately political reasons in a very politically fraught

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:01.990
moment, I should say.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.740
You also had Congress pressuring Apple News over leftist bias

00:12:05.740 --> 00:12:06.000
.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.440
So in both these examples, you have a government that is

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:15.710
pushing technology providers to change how their algorithms work in order to

00:12:15.930 --> 00:12:19.000
better align with that regime's interests.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:23.990
And then just this month, you have Google trialing,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:29.000
basically replacing human written headlines with AI headlines.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:35.290
And you also have the superhuman experts controversy where they have

00:12:35.290 --> 00:12:39.300
Grammarly effectively had this new feature that they've since

00:12:39.340 --> 00:12:43.580
killed where it would offer writing advice from your favorite journalists just

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:46.460
to promise they didn't ask the journalists if they could use

00:12:46.480 --> 00:12:47.000
their names.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.740
So basically, I'm trying to get out of all this

00:12:49.740 --> 00:12:50.000
.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:51.000
I'm trying to make a point here.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.240
And my point is ultimately, why do we still trust big

00:12:54.240 --> 00:12:55.990
tech with news distribution?

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.500
There's lots of reasons why we probably shouldn't at this

00:12:58.500 --> 00:12:59.000
point.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:05.420
Back when I was growing up, my local paper used to

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:09.110
hire people to ride around on bicycles, usually like elementary and

00:13:09.110 --> 00:13:11.740
high school students, and chuck papers onto people's front lawn

00:13:11.750 --> 00:13:12.000
s.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.890
That was a very core function of the newspaper and it related

00:13:14.890 --> 00:13:16.000
to distribution.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.830
Since then, in the internet era, we've basically handed

00:13:20.830 --> 00:13:24.290
that entire part of the business to tech companies whose interests are

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:28.660
often not aligned with that of journalism or that of just public

00:13:28.660 --> 00:13:30.000
information.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
So with that, a couple of questions.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.020
One, wouldn't it be cool if journalism wasn't held

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:38.710
hostage by large tech companies and the billionaires who owned them

00:13:38.710 --> 00:13:38.990
?

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.910
And furthermore, wouldn't it be cool if journalists and

00:13:41.910 --> 00:13:44.690
news orgs had a say in how users discovered news content

00:13:44.690 --> 00:13:45.000
?

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:46.930
And lastly, wouldn't it be cool if there was more

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:49.990
transparency about why users are seeing news topics on social media?

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.920
At the moment, so much of the way in which news

00:13:52.920 --> 00:13:56.860
is delivered to users is basically like an opaque box that you

00:13:56.860 --> 00:14:00.100
can't look into and you can't really interrogate and

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:03.000
you don't really know why you're receiving the news.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.680
And furthermore, why is this the news of the day

00:14:05.680 --> 00:14:06.000
?

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.040
Wouldn't it be cool if we could kind of work to

00:14:08.430 --> 00:14:10.000
improve all of these things together?

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:14.110
And to some degree, I think custom feeds are an answer

00:14:14.110 --> 00:14:14.990
to that.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.460
And it's one of those things that I think we're

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:22.990
going to have to do some work as builders in the atmosphere

00:14:22.990 --> 00:14:28.000
to try and teach newspapers how to use this technology.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
Because they can start using it.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:31.000
They can start building their own algorithms.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.620
They can start serving content to readers in a way that makes

00:14:33.620 --> 00:14:35.000
sense for that readership.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:36.000
They can start doing it today.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
And frankly, very few have.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
So, these are two feeds I built.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
This is probably what I'm best known for.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:47.500
On the left, you have the OG reverse chronological news

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:52.170
feed, which has about 300-ish odd news orgs

00:14:52.170 --> 00:14:52.980
in it.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.500
And on the right, you have the trending news feed,

00:14:56.500 --> 00:15:00.920
which is the same but using a very arbitrarily weighted trending

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:01.980
algorithm.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.400
I used to just like chose random numbers for the trending news

00:15:04.470 --> 00:15:06.000
feed when I initially like set it up.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:11.160
And it's been really cool working with some researchers in the

00:15:11.160 --> 00:15:11.530
U.

00:15:11.550 --> 00:15:12.000
S.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.960
to try to basically A/B test various versions of the

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:20.880
feed with different weights to see which delivers the most user satisfaction

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:23.000
for consuming the news.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:24.000
And I think it's really interesting.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.880
As somebody who works in the journalism space, who's created

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:29.880
a feed of news for users to then work with researchers to

00:15:29.890 --> 00:15:32.260
try and improve the news reading experience for readers, not so

00:15:32.260 --> 00:15:36.180
much that increases their engagement or whatever, but so that they

00:15:36.180 --> 00:15:38.450
can have a better news reading experience, so they can see

00:15:38.450 --> 00:15:40.610
more local news, so they can see more things that are

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:41.000
relevant to them.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.590
Instead of just whatever hot button topic is just wanting to be

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:47.990
pushed in front of them by the major traditional media.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.560
So my news feeds together, we have about 80,000

00:15:51.580 --> 00:15:54.170
DAUs, and in the context of, say,

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:58.690
Twitter's discovery feed or a lot of the other big platforms

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:01.720
, 80,000 DAUs, it's not much

00:16:01.720 --> 00:16:01.990
.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
But to start, it puts it going to be done.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:09.190
And I think that's a point that we need to start

00:16:09.190 --> 00:16:12.460
bringing to news orgs, the fact that you can do

00:16:12.460 --> 00:16:13.990
these things now.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:17.310
This is, and furthermore, you can do things that

00:16:17.310 --> 00:16:20.000
, like, you can do it fairly easily.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.520
This is my graze page for the news feed, and

00:16:22.520 --> 00:16:25.320
there's a button that I've circled up top saying

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:26.000
remix.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.120
And if you want to create your own version of the feed

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:32.000
, say you want to exclude the onion from it.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.160
The one satirical paper I have in the news feed

00:16:34.270 --> 00:16:35.000
is the onion.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.170
I kind of just take it as given that in 2026

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:39.490
you should probably know that the onion is a satirical

00:16:39.490 --> 00:16:39.990
paper.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.830
I still have people constantly asking me to remove it, though

00:16:41.830 --> 00:16:42.000
.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:43.740
If you want to, though, you can remix the feed

00:16:43.740 --> 00:16:45.000
and remove the onion from it.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.000
There you go.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:47.000
I would, though.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:48.000
I love the onion.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:49.790
Or say you want to change, like, a sorting option

00:16:49.790 --> 00:16:50.000
.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.680
Or say you want to make it so that, you know

00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:54.990
, image posts aren't allowed.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:56.000
You can do that.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.000
You can click remix.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:00.720
It will create a new version of my feed in your account

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:01.000
.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
It will still use the same list of orgs and whatnot

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:03.000
.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:08.010
And you can then have that as a personalized, improved source

00:17:08.050 --> 00:17:09.000
of news.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:13.220
And similarly, Graze recently released a new feature called,

00:17:13.220 --> 00:17:17.140
it effectively uses a similar algorithm to the 4U feed to

00:17:17.140 --> 00:17:19.000
find personalized content.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:21.610
And in, like, five minutes of work, I created

00:17:21.610 --> 00:17:24.090
a new version of the feed that is, like, very

00:17:24.090 --> 00:17:27.000
personalized to my news viewing habits.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And anybody who uses Graze can just do this.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.150
And news orgs that, you know, create their own

00:17:34.150 --> 00:17:38.650
feeds can create different ways in which users can view that content

00:17:38.650 --> 00:17:38.990
.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
How many of you have per time, by the way?

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:46.000
Sorry.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:47.000
Okay, cool.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
Thank you.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:50.000
So, yeah.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.290
So these are two examples of, like, ways that news

00:17:53.290 --> 00:17:57.740
orgs or feeds could work in a kind of more localized

00:17:57.750 --> 00:17:58.980
capacity.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Like, so my two feeds are very, very global.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.470
They're world news orgs, reverse chronological training as

00:18:04.470 --> 00:18:05.000
it is.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.080
But you can also do things that are more specific to your

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:09.990
news org and to that audience.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.370
On the left is the Financial Times staff feed, which is

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:14.000
a feed that I may have helped with.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:20.790
And it's effectively anybody who the Financial Times account follows in

00:18:20.790 --> 00:18:21.990
one feed.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:23.000
And, like, I kind of love it.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.980
Like, I use it, like, myself, like,

00:18:24.980 --> 00:18:26.000
on a daily basis.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.800
It's one of the first feeds I check in the morning

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:28.000
.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.360
Because it has all the contributors for the FT, you can

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:34.380
see what are those journalists talking about at a glance in one

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:34.990
place.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.000
And you can pan it to your home screen.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.090
And if you're a reader of that paper and you really

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:40.990
care deeply about what those journalists are talking about or thinking about

00:18:40.990 --> 00:18:43.000
, you can see that really quickly.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
Similarly, you have Rich Ferro's Minneapolis ICE feed,

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.310
which I think is, like, a great example of using

00:18:48.310 --> 00:18:50.000
feeds in, like, a hyperlocal context.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:53.240
Taking a topic that is really relevant to the local community and

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:58.550
taking a combination of news content, local writers, individuals who

00:18:58.550 --> 00:19:00.000
are impacted, and putting it into one place.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:01.880
And I think that there's, like, a lot of

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:04.990
really interesting use cases like this that local news can do.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.470
But maybe part of the problem that why I haven't really

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:10.570
seen a lot of examples like this is just because they're

00:19:10.580 --> 00:19:11.990
not really aware of this technology.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:15.960
And so with that, I think, you know, a

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:20.240
big part of what we need to do as builders is sort

00:19:20.240 --> 00:19:24.000
of popularizing this technology and trying things and just building feeds

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:24.000
.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.430
And, you know, whether it's using Graze or

00:19:26.470 --> 00:19:28.990
, like, Surf is also really, really exciting.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:30.480
I mentioned Graze a lot, but Surf is super,

00:19:30.480 --> 00:19:31.000
super cool.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
I've been playing with that a little bit.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
I love the interface for it.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:39.990
The new thing they mentioned earlier could also be cool.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:43.890
But, like, ultimately there are many, and there's

00:19:43.900 --> 00:19:46.000
also, like, yeah.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:47.790
So, but anyways, there's a lot of routes to

00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:49.000
create custom feeds now.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.060
And I think, you know, I would encourage people to

00:19:52.060 --> 00:19:53.990
just start building things.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.560
If you don't have a source of news that you need

00:19:57.580 --> 00:20:00.000
on AT Proto, just build it.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:03.420
You can just do things and share with people and tell people

00:20:03.440 --> 00:20:06.660
about it and tell them why it's useful because it's

00:20:06.660 --> 00:20:09.490
kind of up to us to popularize this technology because at

00:20:09.490 --> 00:20:12.000
the moment it's kind of hard to find.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:16.090
It's kind of not exactly obvious for people who are new

00:20:16.090 --> 00:20:18.990
to blue sky or to the atmosphere more generally.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:23.000
Why should media orcs create custom feeds?

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.000
Because it connects their journalists with their audience.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.110
If you make one for your paper, like the FT Staff

00:20:28.270 --> 00:20:32.720
ord I mentioned, you can give them this very close kind

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:35.820
of, like, summary of everything that your journalists are talking

00:20:35.820 --> 00:20:37.850
about, which, again, if you're a subscriber,

00:20:37.850 --> 00:20:39.000
you might care about.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:43.300
If you have multiple verticals, for instance, you can

00:20:43.300 --> 00:20:45.000
use a custom feed to unify them into one place.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:48.480
And so even if you have multiple accounts or publishing various other

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:51.530
places, you can consolidate them into, like, a singular

00:20:51.530 --> 00:20:52.000
feed.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
You can also highlight top content.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.810
You can use pin posts to do promotions or to, like

00:20:56.810 --> 00:21:01.150
, highlight a particular editorial kind of, like, campaign or

00:21:01.150 --> 00:21:03.000
something of that nature.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.700
One thing I would really like to see is custom feeds being

00:21:05.700 --> 00:21:08.000
used as a way of promoting, say, subscription deals.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.990
Say you have a subscription sale going on.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.330
You could use a rotating post to just put a little note

00:21:15.470 --> 00:21:16.960
being like, "Hey, do you want to see this

00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:18.000
content without a paywall?

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:22.380
Buy a subscription over here." There's lots of cool things

00:21:22.380 --> 00:21:24.650
that, like, a news org could do with a custom

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:27.290
feed that maybe they're sleeping on and you need to tell

00:21:27.470 --> 00:21:28.000
them about.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:31.010
And most importantly, all this stuff is, like, kind

00:21:31.010 --> 00:21:32.000
of free to use.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.640
It doesn't require a huge capital outlay from a news

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:37.000
org, most of which are increasingly cash-strapped,

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.750
to be able to try these things and to do these things

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:40.000
.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:44.610
And one thing also that I would love to see is journalism

00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:47.990
societies start to use custom feeds.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:51.270
Not just newspapers, but kind of the civil society organizations around

00:21:51.270 --> 00:21:52.000
journalism.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:54.000
So, like, in the UK we have the NU

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:57.000
J, which is the National Union of Journalists.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.380
And we also have IPSO, which is one of our

00:21:59.470 --> 00:22:01.000
many press regulators.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:06.740
These are organizations that are kind of connected with journalism but don

00:22:06.740 --> 00:22:09.000
't produce a lot of journalism themselves quite often.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:13.650
They can use some of these technologies to do really cool things

00:22:13.650 --> 00:22:13.990
.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:15.810
Say you're, like, a union of journalists, right

00:22:15.810 --> 00:22:16.000
?

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:19.000
You do your yearly renewal and you send out your form,

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:20.000
"Hey, are you still a practicing journalist?

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:21.000
Where are you at?

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:23.900
Could I get some details, updates?" You've got a

00:22:23.900 --> 00:22:26.000
form saying, "What is your Blue Sky Handle?"

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.460
And then suddenly you have a big database of all of the

00:22:28.490 --> 00:22:31.270
journalists in your organization who have Blue Sky Handles, put

00:22:31.270 --> 00:22:34.120
them onto a custom feed, and suddenly you have a really

00:22:34.120 --> 00:22:38.050
good source of, like, independent journalism from the journalists who

00:22:38.050 --> 00:22:40.000
are either working at titles or are freelance.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:41.640
One of the, I think, biggest kind of things that

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:44.540
, like, I wish the news feed could do better would

00:22:44.540 --> 00:22:49.820
be to surface freelance journalists and surface individual contributors kind of in

00:22:49.820 --> 00:22:50.990
that space.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:54.000
I kind of bolted the idea of, you know,

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:57.000
verifying every single journalist who came to me on Blue Sky

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:58.000
asking if you add to a feed.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
So I didn't really do an individual journalist feed.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.450
It would be really easy if you're, like, you

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:04.990
know, a journalist union, for instance.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:07.750
And there's lots of, kind of, various things you

00:23:07.750 --> 00:23:09.000
could do with that.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:11.000
You could, here's a wild idea.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:12.880
Say, like, you're a journalism org, like the

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:15.270
NUJ, like I mentioned, and you get a

00:23:15.270 --> 00:23:18.000
trusted verifier status.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:21.420
Suddenly you can verify independent journalists who are working, might not

00:23:21.440 --> 00:23:24.120
have access to the verification facilities that, like, a major

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:24.990
newspaper would have.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.140
I think there's, like, a lot of tools for

00:23:27.470 --> 00:23:32.990
specifically independent titles and for small publishers that the atmosphere provides that

00:23:32.990 --> 00:23:37.000
we really need to start talking to news orgs about.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:42.080
Because it can really change how they do things and really kind

00:23:42.080 --> 00:23:46.320
of improve some of the, you know, give them more

00:23:46.490 --> 00:23:50.980
traffic and be able to use the platform better.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.560
Another point that I've been trying to make a little bit

00:23:53.560 --> 00:23:56.220
over the last little while is I kind of feel increasingly that

00:23:56.220 --> 00:23:59.000
journalism in 2026 is more than just reportage.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:02.420
It's not simply taking view from nowhere, reporting the facts

00:24:02.450 --> 00:24:03.990
journalism all the time.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.530
A lot of the time, like, in my mind in

00:24:06.530 --> 00:24:11.680
some ways as doing journalism in 2026 means helping the audience

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:14.000
navigate this news climate.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:21.650
Steve Bannon in 2016 had the expression filling the, filling

00:24:21.650 --> 00:24:23.000
the zone with shit.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:28.150
Which is basically the idea of creating so much just nonsense in

00:24:28.150 --> 00:24:31.090
the press that people don't really know where to focus or

00:24:31.090 --> 00:24:33.000
know where to, like, focus their attentions on.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:36.280
And I think kind of some of those slides earlier talking about

00:24:36.280 --> 00:24:39.680
news avoidance is a good indication that that strategy has been

00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:41.000
kind of successful.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:44.060
So how do we as creators and builders and how do we

00:24:44.060 --> 00:24:48.110
also as journalists start to use these tools to start unpacking

00:24:48.110 --> 00:24:48.990
the zone?

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:52.000
I've had a few ideas.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.960
On the left you have xBlock which is probably,

00:24:54.990 --> 00:24:58.540
I think it's Blue Sky's longest running third party lab

00:24:58.540 --> 00:24:59.000
eler.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:02.650
I built this back in, I think, 20, 24

00:25:02.670 --> 00:25:03.000
?

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:05.000
And it's been running ever since then.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:09.080
It labels screenshots from social media platforms, whether it be Twitter

00:25:09.080 --> 00:25:11.000
or Blue Sky itself or threads or whatever.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.580
I need to really train the model because it's basically labeling

00:25:13.580 --> 00:25:17.000
most things as Twitter right now, but it works.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.000
And I think people find it very, very useful as a

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:25.900
way of kind of turning down the volume on their social media

00:25:25.930 --> 00:25:27.000
experience.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:31.250
By not seeing screenshots dunking from Twitter, they're able

00:25:31.250 --> 00:25:33.710
to have a kind of, like, cleaner, less emot

00:25:33.710 --> 00:25:35.000
ive sort of social media experience.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:37.250
And kind of like, you know, my experience with x

00:25:37.300 --> 00:25:39.690
Block has informed two new labelers that I've created

00:25:39.690 --> 00:25:39.990
.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.000
They're very much in development.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.000
They're a little bit trash right now.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:45.610
Be forewarned if you, like, subscribe to

00:25:45.610 --> 00:25:46.000
them.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
But I'm working on them.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:49.720
They're a work in progress and I'll explain what they

00:25:49.720 --> 00:25:50.000
are.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:53.000
In the middle you have Media Ownership Labeler.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.620
I have this big list of all the titles in the news

00:25:55.620 --> 00:25:59.000
feed and I've tried to manually go through and figure out

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:00.000
what their funding model is.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:03.000
Whether they're independently funded or whether they have, like,

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:04.990
a big corporate owner, like, say, Condé Nast

00:26:04.990 --> 00:26:06.000
or something like that.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
Or whether they're, like, reader supported.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:10.840
And what it allows you to do, it allows you to

00:26:10.840 --> 00:26:12.000
do two things.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.570
First thing is you can have just, like, a little

00:26:14.570 --> 00:26:17.570
badge on every news title saying, like, what their funding

00:26:17.580 --> 00:26:18.000
model is.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:19.720
So if you're just scrolling the news feed and you're

00:26:19.720 --> 00:26:21.000
kind of curious, you can see that.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:22.890
The cool thing is if you want to block all of R

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:24.650
upert Murdoch's papers, you can do that

00:26:24.670 --> 00:26:25.000
.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:28.000
The last one is News Classifier.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:29.020
And this is, like, an idea that I've had

00:26:29.020 --> 00:26:30.000
for, like, a really long time.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:33.560
I've wanted to find a way of classifying the content

00:26:33.630 --> 00:26:36.000
being emitted by the news feed.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.500
It uses -- and I only actually managed to figure out how

00:26:38.500 --> 00:26:39.000
to do this.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:41.050
This idea has been circling in my head for about,

00:26:41.050 --> 00:26:42.000
like, a year now.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.090
But I only managed to figure out how to do it about

00:26:44.090 --> 00:26:45.000
a fortnight ago.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:51.000
This is kind of driven by getting a lot of requests for

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.000
kind of get the news feed but without sports.

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:55.000
Or the news feed without entertainment.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.940
And it's kind of hard because news orgs publish all

00:26:57.940 --> 00:27:01.990
genres of content under, like, the same account name.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:07.610
So I have a very, very light BERT text classification

00:27:07.610 --> 00:27:12.000
model that's looking at the OG tags of news orgs

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.770
, or news posts that are being emitted by the news feed

00:27:14.770 --> 00:27:15.000
.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.220
And it tries to add a label to them, which is

00:27:17.440 --> 00:27:19.000
used for downstream tooling.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:21.500
Say you want to create a version of the news feed without

00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:25.000
sports, you can do that pretty easily using Graze.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:28.190
It uses Contrails, which is a Graze feature

00:27:28.190 --> 00:27:31.490
that gives you, like, a web socket of all the

00:27:31.530 --> 00:27:35.000
content being emitted by a particular custom feed.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:38.280
And it makes the infrastructure side of it, like, a

00:27:38.280 --> 00:27:39.990
lot easier to deal with.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:42.000
Okay.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.000
I think that's it.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:47.000
Thank you.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.310
If you want to try remixing the news feed, gra

00:27:49.470 --> 00:27:49.820
ze.

00:27:49.820 --> 00:27:52.000
social/feed/396.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:54.300
Again, encourage everyone to, like, try and create their

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:58.000
own news sources and try and, like, use this technology

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
to create a better understanding of news.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:01.580
I'm open to questions if anyone has them, but I

00:28:01.580 --> 00:28:03.000
'm in trouble answering questions.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:04.000
Hi.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:11.000
Excellent.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:11.000
Okay.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:12.890
So we have a few minutes to answer some, or to

00:28:12.890 --> 00:28:14.000
take some questions.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:15.000
Do you have a question?

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:16.000
All right.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:17.000
Matt.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:18.000
Thanks, Henry.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:19.000
Quick question.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:20.830
What do you think about permissioned data and what that offers

00:28:20.830 --> 00:28:21.000
?

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
Perhaps new subscription products?

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:25.000
Maybe bundled subscription products?

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:28.240
So people can subscribe to a custom feed and get content that

00:28:28.240 --> 00:28:31.000
they wouldn't find on, like, on the main,

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:31.990
on the open.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:34.280
I don't know, a subscription product, basically, that

00:28:34.470 --> 00:28:35.000
could be sold.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:37.000
Could you actually generate revenue for news organizations?

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.560
So, like, kind of, like, yeah, so

00:28:39.560 --> 00:28:42.010
I think a big part of it is, like, the

00:28:42.050 --> 00:28:44.000
private data story for AT Proto.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:45.830
Like, until there's, like, more, you know

00:28:45.830 --> 00:28:48.270
, private data, I think, will facilitate more, and

00:28:48.270 --> 00:28:50.310
, like, permissioned data, I think is how they

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:52.400
're referring to it, will facilitate that kind of thing a

00:28:52.400 --> 00:28:52.970
lot better.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:56.000
There's already some stuff you can do with Graze.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
Excuse me.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.720
I think Graze has, like, some kind of,

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:02.990
like, Patreon integration.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
I'm not entirely sure how that works.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:06.680
But I think the idea with that is to be able to

00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:09.000
post into the feed you need to be a Patreon subscriber.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.000
So it's kind of like a subscriber feed.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.650
And so I think there are kind of things like that that

00:29:13.650 --> 00:29:15.990
, you know, could be useful approaches.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:18.530
Again, though, like, the lack of permission data kind

00:29:18.530 --> 00:29:21.880
of makes it challenging to do subscribers-only sort of stuff

00:29:21.890 --> 00:29:26.000
, I think, kind of on the platform.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:27.000
Hello.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:32.830
I have a question around -- so we would love to work

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:37.000
with more newsrooms, journalists, all of it.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.760
And I think one of the difficult things that we have when

00:29:39.760 --> 00:29:41.750
we're messaging to them, and maybe you can help me

00:29:41.750 --> 00:29:44.320
with, is that -- and I haven't worked with news

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:46.840
rooms, so this is mostly from, like, indie publishers

00:29:46.860 --> 00:29:48.830
, maybe on Substack, like, that kind of thing

00:29:48.840 --> 00:29:49.000
.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
That reach is really everything.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:55.000
Like, it has to get you more views.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:58.000
If it does that, everything else kind of is good.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:00.000
Well, maybe not good, but fine.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:04.560
And the atmosphere ecosystem is not yet at a scale where I

00:30:04.560 --> 00:30:08.660
can promise someone, like, 2x views or anything like

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:08.970
that.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:12.000
But all this feed stuff is incredible.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:17.270
So how do I talk about that in a way that respects

00:30:17.270 --> 00:30:25.030
that kind of, like, discovery portion and highlights the things

00:30:25.030 --> 00:30:26.990
that we can do?

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:28.000
Yeah.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:29.000
That's a big question.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:30.000
And that one's really hard.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:35.010
That's, you know, convincing news orgs to switch

00:30:35.050 --> 00:30:38.600
en masse to Blue Sky, and potentially even, like,

00:30:38.600 --> 00:30:40.000
exclusively to Blue Sky.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.700
First of all, the exclusivity thing isn't going to

00:30:42.700 --> 00:30:44.990
happen because news orgs are like that.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:49.920
But also, the -- you know, the more reach the

00:30:49.920 --> 00:30:52.410
platform has, the easier it is to make this case to

00:30:52.410 --> 00:30:53.000
news orgs.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:55.450
And right now, Blue Sky's reach is not what the

00:30:55.490 --> 00:30:57.000
commercial platform is.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.000
That's just the long and short of it.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:04.010
I think part of it is we need to increase that user

00:31:04.050 --> 00:31:05.000
base.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.870
And my feeling is that one way to do that is by

00:31:07.870 --> 00:31:11.000
creating better news reading experiences.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.680
If you create a news reading experience that, you know,

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:20.010
privileges people's time and doesn't kind of overwhelm them

00:31:20.080 --> 00:31:22.990
nearly as much, that might be, like, one route

00:31:22.990 --> 00:31:26.380
in which we can start building more traffic on, like,

00:31:26.380 --> 00:31:29.000
AT Proto, for news consuming experiences.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.550
What Surf's doing really, you know, excites me

00:31:31.550 --> 00:31:34.290
because it's a way of doing something that's not just

00:31:34.290 --> 00:31:37.070
on AT Proto, but also on Activity Pub,

00:31:37.070 --> 00:31:39.590
and pulling together these disparate sources of content in a way

00:31:39.610 --> 00:31:42.550
that is, like, kind of engaging, but also,

00:31:42.560 --> 00:31:45.780
like, very, you know, respective of your mental energy

00:31:45.790 --> 00:31:46.000
.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:50.190
I really like how they have filters on Surf to hide politics

00:31:50.190 --> 00:31:52.000
content or Elon Musk.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:55.260
I think, like, yeah, I think part of it

00:31:55.260 --> 00:32:00.400
is we need to just create better news reading experiences and people

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:02.000
will start gravitating towards them.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:05.290
But, yeah, the question of getting news orgs onto

00:32:05.290 --> 00:32:12.000
the platform is challenging, I think, like, yeah.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:14.940
One thing I did with the news feed, like, initially

00:32:14.940 --> 00:32:17.670
, was required that all the orgs in it have domain

00:32:17.670 --> 00:32:18.990
verified handles.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:23.590
It's called the verified news feed because I required anybody in

00:32:23.590 --> 00:32:27.500
it -- this is before blue ticks were a thing on blue

00:32:27.500 --> 00:32:30.000
sky -- I required them to have a domain handle.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:33.690
So I could actually verify they are who they say they are

00:32:33.690 --> 00:32:34.000
.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:38.510
And I think in doing that, that pushed them to use

00:32:38.510 --> 00:32:44.660
a primary affordance of the platform, which kind of sort

00:32:44.680 --> 00:32:49.080
of gave -- kind of put a bit of effort to do

00:32:49.090 --> 00:32:50.000
that.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.420
They had to talk to their tech people to do the DNS

00:32:52.480 --> 00:32:53.000
entry.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.630
They had to -- you know, once you've invested that

00:32:55.630 --> 00:32:57.990
much effort into a platform, it's, you know,

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.040
it's harder for someone to just be, like, oh

00:33:00.040 --> 00:33:01.000
, we're not getting enough traffic from here.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:02.550
Let's just, like, you know, kill that entire

00:33:02.550 --> 00:33:03.000
account.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:04.000
So, I don't know.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.940
I think kind of encouraging news orgs to use primary afford

00:33:06.940 --> 00:33:10.000
ance of the platform, like custom feeds, like labelers

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:11.570
, is one way we start to build interest kind of in

00:33:11.570 --> 00:33:13.000
that space, I think, a little bit.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.730
I'm not sure if I've answered your question, but

00:33:15.730 --> 00:33:17.990
it's a bunch of scattered thoughts.

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:19.320
It's a problem.
